meme, Etymology, Coined by British biologist Richard Dawkins in 1976 in his book The Selfish Gene. Shortened (after gene) from mimeme, 
verb 创造（新词，短语），杜撰 
meme(plural memes), Any unit of cultural information, such as a practice or idea, that is transmitted verbally or by repeated action from one mind to another in a comparable way to the transmission of genes. (Internet, slang) Something, usually humorous, which is copied and circulated online with slight adaptations, including quizzes, basic pictures, video templates etc.
slang俚语   adaptation适合,适应,顺应 改造,改装,改建; 改编 quiz noun (pl. quizzes)知识测验；智力竞赛，问答比赛 
(Internet slang) A myth circulating as truth; something ineffective presented as effective, or similar.
myth神话 （普遍持有的）错误见解（或想法） ineffective不起作用的；无效的 

Why aren't people talking about 3D printing anymore?
A2A, Because it failed to live up to the hype.

The hype was “Buy this thing! Make more things! Make anything you like!”

The reality was “Buy this thing! It’s cranky and fiddly and sometimes fails in really spectacular ways. It makes rough things, sorta, when it works. The software that runs it is ugly and fiddly and fussy, and requires vast amounts of faffing to get right. It can make some things, as long as there are no significant undercuts or arches, but it’s really slow even when it does work. Oh, and 3D modeling software has an enormous learning curve.”

It has quite a few genuine uses, but they tend to be niche cases. The more breathless predictions—“don’t buy anything any more, just download plans and make things yourself!”—aren’t even close to true.

I use my 3D printer heavily, because I’ve found one of those niche uses; I use it to 3D print molds for silicone sex toys.




But for everyday use? Well, there’s a reason if you look on sites that distribute models for 3D printers, a fair wedge of what they have on offer is…parts for 3D printers. That’s a sure sign of a device still searching for its killer app.



First and foremost, you need to have the right frame of mind or mindset in order to attain English mastery.

This is a harsh reality, by virtue of the fact that English is our global lingua franca today.

As a matter of fact, it's the Language of the 21st Century!

Putting this mindset into tactical terms, this means that you have got to integrate your learning of English into your everyday lifestyle.

Do not approach your learning from the standpoint of ESL or EFL. [ESL=English as Second Language; EFL=English as Foreign Language].

ENGLISH IS A LIFE SKILL!

In other words, you must not confine your learning of English to the spending of prescribed hours you are studying or learning in a classroom, within four walls in a school.

It is important for you to understand that English mastery also involves the acquisition of five critical skills sets,

1) Reading;
2)Thinking;
3) Listening;
4) Speaking;
5) Writing;

as applied in your everyday life experiences of the real world.

Like the five spokes of a wheel held all together by the rim with the tyre revolving around the hub, each of these areas need to be strong in order for the wheel to run smoothly on the road, just as you need the five skill sets in order for you to attain English mastery.

Seek every opportunity in your daily events and activities to learn - and master - English.

Initially, you can segregate them as follows, in tandem with the foregoing skill sets,

1) Reading;

- Perusing an English story book, preferably written for children as it may be easier for you to follow at the beginning, at least regularly, or the daily local English newspaper, but don't forget to reflect on the key ideas like the genre, plot, theme, setting, characters, critical events (climax), interesting phrases/words, personal impressions or feelings about the story, lessons learned, in the case of the story, or current issues of the day, as reported in the newspaper;

[If you are interested, you can explore the use of storyboards and storygrids to help you further in this particular area.]

- use Index Card Strategy for your vocabulary building and generation;
- if you are interested, you can explore/apply SQ5R in your reading pursuit [Just Google for it on the net];

2) Thinking;

- Finding one daily news article in your native language, and translating it into English; this is absolutely good practice to perfect your thinking and writing in English;
- Make it a daily habit to simply think of a problem or a challenge or an issue from your daily observations or reflections, and explore various ideas to resolve them, and then, pretend you are giving an oral presentation of your solutions to an audience;

3) Listening;

- Watching an English movie without subtitles, and paying particular attention to interesting dialogues and memorable quotes; don't forget to jot them down for review;
- Listening to pod-casts in English or the English news broadcasts; don't forget to jot down the salient points for review or self-talk;
- Watching YouTube video clips in English, and pausing in between to repeat what you have just heard; this is to practise your listening skills;

4) Speaking;

- Using FaceTime or Skype to converse with international friends, who speak English;
- Striking up casual conversations with Caucasian folks in the queue, say at any Starbucks or in any supermarket;
- Calling up customer service of MNC's and pretending to put forward your complaint;
- Dropping by a large hotel reception and pretending to check up the hotel for a forthcoming party of international friends, to seek opportunities to speak English.
- Singing in the shower with English songs, to practise your pronunciation;

5) Writing;

- Writing letters to international English-speaking pen-pals;
- Selecting interesting topics from your daily events or activities to write up a daily account, at least 250-500 words;

Others,

- Using your smartphone, loaded with "learning English" applications, for daily, spaced and distributed practice;
- you can also join a local chapter of the international Toastmasters' Club to perfect your public speaking. I am sure there is one in your city;

I am just scratching the surface, and am sure you can think of more ideas to help yourself in having a systematic way to master the English Language.

Meanwhile, I like to recommend you to carry a pocket notebook with you at all times.

Whenever you are on the streets, pay attention to the wall posters, billboards, window displays, bulletin boards or even signboards. If you come across new words, jot them down in your pocket notebook for reviewing at home with the aid of a dictionary.

Then, use your Index Card Strategy to master these new words.

Make it a habit to learn at least ten new words a day. In a year, you would have learned more than 3,500 words!

Look around you. Can you identify all the places or landmarks in English. If not, jot them down for reviewing at home.

Likewise, in the supermarket, ask yourself, can you identify all the items on display, in English? If not, you can start learning to read the labels.

Take note of casual conversations around you. Go home and review them. Better still, do a simulated conversation on your own, aloud, and in front of a mirror. You can record and review, too.

Upon reading a story book, or listening to a news broadcast, or watching a movie, spend a few minutes to recap the key ideas or salient issues of the day or the key plot of the movie, but more importantly for you, the lessons you have learned.

You can use the famed 6W1H questioning toolkit often used by journalists to spur your questions and expand your thinking.

Then, grab a sheet of blank paper and start writing down your answers as you think. In reality, these initiatives offer great opportunities - and practices - for you to think and write in English.

Frankly, the world out there is full of possibilities and opportunities when it comes to learning English. It's an invisible university!

One last point before I sign off, You can develop a system to learn and master English, but the fire test comes only from your consistent and massive following-up and following-through.

Godspeed to you!



The best way to improve anything is to start doing it. If you want to cook better, you need to start cooking. If you want better grades, you need to start studying. Similarly the only way to improve your English speaking skills is to start conversing in English. Many people feel bogged down or humiliated due to a certain inability to converse better in a foreign language. They start blaming their 'Hindi medium' background or how they were brought up in a town, but all this is of no use. Start forming groups with your friends and decide to converse with them only in English. You could also have certain sessions every week with your friends and family where every participant would be required to give a speech or organize an extempore event. This would not only improve your English skills but also remove the fear of speaking before an audience i.e. the so-called 'stage fear' would be conquered.
But as a dish is incomplete without all its ingredients, learning new words is a must if one desires to command a language. For that, I would suggest 'Word Power Made Easy' by Norman Lewis which covers hundreds of words in separate chapters and makes the entire learning process very simple through elaborate and comprehensive exercises. It is available at a very nominal price and is according to me the best book to improve English vocabulary.
But the most important thing is to get rid of those inhibitions that we all have and the desire to learn something new which you clearly possess. So best of luck and I'm sure that you would improve you vocab & speaking skills in English.



Trying to learn a language the same way a baby does is a silly idea, and I wish language-learning programs would stop putting it in people's heads. For one, it's impossible. Babies are acquiring their first language when they are learning, but an adult has already acquired a language. It's impossible to re-create that effect on the brain. Secondly, think about how well Chinese children speak when they are 4 or 5 years old. That's after 4 or 5 years of nothing but Chinese language immersion, with two permanent live-in Chinese teachers named 'Mom' and 'Dad'. Monolingual English-speaking children speak English poorly, even though they have spoken no other language for their entire lives. I'd much rather hire someone who had studied English (or Chinese) for 5 years over someone who spoke English (or Chinese) like a 5-year-old.

As an adult, you have much more life experience than a baby. You are capable of studying, taking notes, making connections and practicing in ways that small children simply cannot. You can learn faster and better than they can. The reason language learning is 'easier for kids' is because they're fearless--there is no social risk if they make a mistake. The reason language learning is 'easier for adults' is because they've already learned a language before, and probably many other very complicated skills, too--they have prior experience in learning difficult systems, and have an existing system to compare and contrast to. Adults have abstract thinking abilities that children don't. Adults also have something called 'metalinguistic awareness', which means you can think about language and understand things like metaphor, allusion, jokes, wordplay, how situation and tone of voice changes meaning, etc. and you have a greater ability to manipulate language than a child does. This is a big advantage for adult language learners.

Now, as for your question about learning like a child...

I'm currently an English language teacher abroad, and with the 3-6 year olds I teach, we only learn 3 words a day. Trust me, as a 23-year-old person, repeating 'I'm hungry! I'm hungry! I'm hungry! I'm hungry!' over and over again would be embarrassing and a waste of time--as would going back and chanting 'I'm hungry! I'm hungry! I'm hungry!' again five minutes later to make sure you haven't forgotten it. For a 3 or 4-year-old child, you have to do this because they will forget (or will refuse to participate the first time), and they have a hard time retaining 9 or 10 new phrases in the target language, when they spend 23 hours out of the day in a monolingual environment. But you're an adult--you CAN retain more information, and you can choose to practice more throughout the day in various ways that a 3-year-old can't. My low-level adult students have classes that are the same length as the children's classes, but by the end of the lesson, they are able to converse with one another using the target grammar for the day with a variety of new vocabulary terms. And we hardly ever sing The Alphabet Song with the grown-ups, which is always a plus when it comes to dignity.

That being said, American children start out learning to listen and speak before learning how to read. Writing is often the last skill they learn, because fine motor skills don't begin to develop until between the ages of 4-6. That's why children's handwriting looks so bad. They physically can't control the pencil very well. Again, you're an adult, so you can. You've also got a head start, in that you are able to read and write English at a pretty decent level (I didn't have any trouble comprehending what you wrote--the one thing I would suggest right now is that you put a space after all punctuation marks). What you probably need is a conversation tutor, to improve your verbal and aural skills.

Nobody starts out life learning IPA--many adults can't read IPA, and very few things are written in IPA anyway. We simply sound out words based on past experience with the language and learn the correct pronunciations through trial and error, or through having them modeled by another speaker. Many English words are mispronounced every day by native English speakers.



They can only be paired up in particular ways. It's okay to say "this evening" or "yesterday evening" but not "this night" or "yesterday night." But, "tomorrow night" and "tomorrow evening" are both okay. "Yesterday afternoon" is okay, but "last afternoon" is not. "Last evening" is not okay.

THIS MAKES ABSOLUTELY NO SENSE. (Unless a linguist wants to chime in here?)



No, they are generally unsuitable materials for learning English. They have the same built-in defects that you described Chinese songs have.

Songs are songs, and while they have a lot of the language in 'normal' form, the whole thing doesn't reflect everyday usage.

It's like trying to learn the everyday textures and operations of English from studying Shakespeare -- English speakers simply don't speak Shakespearean anymore. Same difference with songs.



